(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 12 :title "Chapter 12 — Symbolic differentiation" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/12-symbolic-differentiation.md" :size 5017 :sha256 "9f537263f51c76e7" :content "---\nslug: sakura-scheme-book-reference-12\ntitle: Symbolic differentiation\nbook: reference\nchapter: 12\nof: 16\npart: II\napp: scheme-repl\npalette: book-standard\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane 6)\nphilosopher-lens: [wittgenstein-tractatus, jung, lacan, peirce, popper, freud, wittgenstein-late, searle]\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-12\nprev: 11-lazy-evaluation\nnext: 13-algebraic-data\n---\n\n# Chapter 12 — Symbolic differentiation\n\nThe SICP-flavored exercise everyone remembers: a program that\ntakes an expression like `(+ x (* 3 x))` and returns the\nderivative with respect to `x`. It's not a big program. It's the\nprogram that convinces you that Scheme is *good at* symbolic\nmanipulation because expressions are data.\n\nThe whole thing is one function, `deriv`, that pattern-matches on\nthe structure of the expression.\n\n## The core\n\n```scheme\n(define (variable? x)   (symbol? x))\n(define (same-variable? v1 v2) (and (variable? v1) (variable? v2) (eq? v1 v2)))\n(define (sum? x)        (and (pair? x) (eq? (car x) '+)))\n(define (addend s)      (cadr s))\n(define (augend s)      (caddr s))\n(define (product? x)    (and (pair? x) (eq? (car x) '*)))\n(define (multiplier p)  (cadr p))\n(define (multiplicand p) (caddr p))\n\n(define (make-sum a b)\n  (cond\n    ((and (number? a) (= a 0)) b)\n    ((and (number? b) (= b 0)) a)\n    ((and (number? a) (number? b)) (+ a b))\n    (else (list '+ a b))))\n\n(define (make-product a b)\n  (cond\n    ((or (and (number? a) (= a 0))\n         (and (number? b) (= b 0))) 0)\n    ((and (number? a) (= a 1)) b)\n    ((and (number? b) (= b 1)) a)\n    ((and (number? a) (number? b)) (* a b))\n    (else (list '* a b))))\n```\n\nThe `make-sum` and `make-product` constructors simplify at\nconstruction time — that's why the output isn't cluttered with\n`(+ 0 x)` or `(* 1 x)`.\n\n## The rules\n\n```scheme\n(define (deriv expr var)\n  (cond\n    ((number? expr) 0)\n    ((variable? expr) (if (same-variable? expr var) 1 0))\n    ((sum? expr)\n     (make-sum (deriv (addend expr)  var)\n               (deriv (augend expr) var)))\n    ((product? expr)\n     (make-sum\n       (make-product (multiplier expr)     (deriv (multiplicand expr) var))\n       (make-product (deriv (multiplier expr) var) (multiplicand expr))))\n    (else\n     (error \"unknown expression\" expr))))\n```\n\nNumbers differentiate to zero. The variable of interest\ndifferentiates to one; any other variable to zero. Sums: derivative\nof a sum is the sum of derivatives. Products: the product rule.\n\n## Try it\n\n```scheme\n(deriv '(+ x 3) 'x)                       ;; => 1\n(deriv '(* x y) 'x)                       ;; => y\n(deriv '(* (* x y) (+ x 3)) 'x)           ;; => (+ (* x y) (* y (+ x 3)))\n```\n\nThe last one is unsimplified but structurally correct. If you\nextend `make-sum` and `make-product` to do more algebraic\nsimplification, the output gets cleaner. That's the exercise.\n\n## Extending: powers\n\n```scheme\n(define (exponentiation? x)\n  (and (pair? x) (eq? (car x) '**)))\n(define (base e)     (cadr e))\n(define (exponent e) (caddr e))\n\n(define (make-exp b n)\n  (cond\n    ((and (number? n) (= n 0)) 1)\n    ((and (number? n) (= n 1)) b)\n    (else (list '** b n))))\n\n;; Extend deriv:\n(define (deriv-with-pow expr var)\n  (cond\n    ((exponentiation? expr)\n     (make-product\n       (make-product (exponent expr)\n                     (make-exp (base expr) (- (exponent expr) 1)))\n       (deriv-with-pow (base expr) var)))\n    ;; ... other cases fall through to deriv\n    (else (deriv expr var))))\n```\n\n`d/dx (x^n) = n * x^(n-1) * d/dx(x)`. Written as a rule, it slots\nright into the pattern.\n\n## Why this exercise matters\n\nThe exercise shows off that expressions and data are the same\nthing in Scheme. `(+ x 3)` is both a program you could evaluate\n*and* a list you can walk. `deriv` walks the list. If Scheme\ndistinguished code from data, this program would be much harder\nto write.\n\nThat property — code as data — is what makes macros work\n(Chapter 4), the metacircular evaluator work (Chapter 6), and the\ntiny compiler work (Chapter 10). Symbolic differentiation is one\nconcrete instance of the pattern.\n\n## Sakura's register on the symbolic exercise\n\nShe likes this exercise. It's small, it works, and it demonstrates\nthe property of Scheme that makes so much else possible. If a\nbeginner is ready for it, she teaches it. If they're not, she\nreaches for something smaller first.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> Symbolic differentiation is the exercise that made *code as\n> data* click for me. The whole thing is walking a tree and\n> applying rules. Once you can walk a tree and apply rules,\n> you can build interpreters, compilers, macros, and about half\n> of the things worth building.\n\n## Exercises\n\n1. Extend `make-sum` to handle three or more arguments cleanly.\n2. Add subtraction: `(- a b)` and its derivative rule.\n3. Add division: `(/ a b)` — the quotient rule is a little more\n   involved. Write `make-div` first.\n4. Simplify `(+ 0 x)` and `(* 1 x)` and `(** x 0)` — extend the\n   constructors to catch these at construction time.\n")
